(appendix
  :book \"book-of-motion\"
  :number 1
  :title \"Winsor McCay and Gertie the Dinosaur\"
  :short-title \"winsor-mccay-gertie\"
  :estimated-words 1400
  :subject-verified \"Zenas Winsor McCay, born ~1867-1871 (his birth date is uncertain, standard reference gives ~1867 or later); died 26 July 1934, Brooklyn, New York.\"
  :film-verified \"Gertie the Dinosaur, first exhibited February 1914, Chicago (vaudeville tour); film version distributed by Box Office Attractions/Fox, late 1914. Public domain.\"
  :philosopher-weave (jung aristotle sartre)

  :prose
\"Winsor McCay was a working newspaper artist. He drew *Little Nemo in Slumberland* for the *New York Herald* from 1905 to 1911, and *Dream of the Rarebit Fiend* under a pseudonym for the *Evening Telegram* around the same time. He supported his family by producing enormous amounts of drawing every week — comic strips, editorial cartoons, illustrated features. He was famously fast and famously precise.

In 1911 he began animating. His first two films (*Little Nemo*, 1911; *How a Mosquito Operates*, 1912) were experimental, showing what could be done with hand-drawn character animation. Then in 1914 he made *Gertie the Dinosaur*.

# What Gertie is

Gertie is a female Apatosaurus. She lives on a small island. The film opens with McCay in top hat and vaudeville coat introducing her from off-screen (the introduction was originally live, spoken by McCay on stage; the film also has intertitle cards for cinema release). McCay calls Gertie out from behind a large boulder. She emerges shyly. Over the next ten minutes McCay directs her through a series of tricks: she raises one foot, she bows, she throws a small mammoth into a lake, she drinks from the lake so heartily that the lake nearly empties. At one point she cries — McCay has scolded her for eating a tree — and the animator, apparently seeing her tears, apologizes to her by feeding her an apple.

The film ends with McCay walking into the frame (or seeming to; the technique is a live-action shot cut into the animated sequence) and Gertie tenderly lifting him with her mouth and carrying him away on her back.

# Why Gertie matters

There had been animated films before Gertie. What Gertie did that hadn't been done before was give the animated character *personality*.

Personality in animation means the audience believes the character has an inner life — that she has preferences, moods, memory, embarrassment, affection. Before Gertie, animated characters had been abstract shapes or figures that moved but didn't feel. Gertie feels bashful when she emerges from behind the rock. She feels stubborn when McCay tells her to do a trick and she looks away. She feels hurt when she is scolded. She feels affectionate when she carries McCay off.

McCay achieved these effects with specific animation techniques that later animators would recognize and formalize:

**Weight in every step.** When Gertie walks, her body settles and lifts with each step. Her weight is visible.

**Anticipation.** Before Gertie does anything, she prepares. Before she leans down to drink, she stretches her neck first.

**Follow-through.** After Gertie moves, her tail continues to swing for a moment. Her body doesn't stop all at once.

**Squash and stretch in the face.** Gertie's expressions come from her whole face flexing — brows raising, cheeks pulling, jaw dropping.

**Pauses.** Gertie sometimes stops between actions, and the stop itself communicates something — hesitation, thought, sulking.

These are all animation-of-personality techniques. McCay figured them out one drawing at a time.

# How McCay made it

McCay drew every frame of Gertie by hand on rice paper. The film runs about ten minutes. At sixteen frames per second (typical silent-cinema rate), that is roughly ten thousand drawings. McCay drew them all himself.

He didn't use cels — cel animation was invented by Earl Hurd the same year and wasn't yet in wide use. That meant McCay had to redraw the *background* on every frame too. Every drawing has Gertie and the island and the lake and the sky, all drawn over again. When Gertie moves, McCay had to keep the background completely consistent across thousands of drawings.

He developed a technique of tracing register marks onto each sheet so the sheets would align exactly. This system — registration for animation — became standard practice.

# The vaudeville presentation

McCay took Gertie on vaudeville tours in 1914. In the theater, McCay would stand in front of the screen dressed as an animal trainer. He would call to Gertie, and the projected Gertie would appear to respond. He would tell her to bow, and she would bow. He would say she was being stubborn, and she would look away. The timing between McCay's spoken cues and the projected film was precise — worked out in advance and rehearsed.

At the end of the performance, McCay would appear to walk into the film — he would step behind a small hidden entrance, and the film would cut to an animated McCay entering the frame. Gertie would lift him on her back and carry him off. Audiences reportedly gasped. The illusion was extraordinary.

# The legacy

Every animated character that has an inner life is a descendant of Gertie. Every audience that laughs or cries at an animated figure is doing so partly because Winsor McCay, in 1914, discovered how to make an animated figure feel.

McCay went on to make *The Sinking of the Lusitania* in 1918 — a serious animated documentary reconstruction of the 1915 sinking, roughly twenty-five thousand drawings, no comedy. It is one of the earliest serious uses of animation for factual subject matter. He continued to animate through the 1920s but was pulled by his newspaper contracts back into daily comic strip work and never made another film on Gertie's scale.

He died in 1934. His son Robert McCay preserved much of his work; it is now held in various archives including the Ohio State University Cartoon Library and the Museum of Modern Art.

# What we can do in Scheme

McCay's essential technique — hand-drawing each frame with careful attention to weight, anticipation, and follow-through — is what modern animators still do, just with different tools. Let's build a small demonstration of a Gertie-like character emerging bashfully from behind a rock.

```scheme
;; A shy emergence: character peeks out, retreats, peeks further, emerges.
;; The retreat-and-return communicates bashfulness.

(define (bashful-emerge frame total-frames)
  (let ((progress (/ frame total-frames)))
    (cond
      ((< progress 0.15)   ; peek out
       (world/place-rock 200 300)
       (world/place-head-behind-rock 220 250 (* progress 40)))

      ((< progress 0.25)   ; retreat
       (world/place-rock 200 300)
       (world/place-head-behind-rock 220 250 (- 6 (* (- progress 0.15) 60))))

      ((< progress 0.5)    ; peek further
       (world/place-rock 200 300)
       (world/place-head-behind-rock 220 250 (* (- progress 0.25) 80)))

      ((< progress 0.6)    ; hesitate
       (world/place-rock 200 300)
       (world/place-head-behind-rock 220 250 20))

      (else                ; emerge
       (let ((x (+ 220 (* (- progress 0.6) 150))))
         (world/place-rock 200 300)
         (world/place-figure x 300 'looking-around))))))

(define (animate-emergence)
  (for-each
    (lambda (f)
      (world/reset!)
      (bashful-emerge f 48)
      (world/render!)
      (world/wait (/ 1.0 12.0)))     ; 12 fps for silent-cinema feel
    (range 0 48)))

(animate-emergence)
```

The peek-retreat-peek-hesitate-emerge pattern is what a shy character does. Watching this animate, the character reads as bashful. That is McCay's discovery: sequence of motion patterns can communicate character.

# Recommended viewing

*Gertie the Dinosaur* (1914). Public domain. Available on multiple archives including the Library of Congress and the Internet Archive.

*The Sinking of the Lusitania* (1918). Also public domain. A very different film — serious, sober, documentary.

*How a Mosquito Operates* (1912). Public domain. McCay's second animated film, showing his development toward Gertie.

# Sources cited

John Canemaker, *Winsor McCay: His Life and Art* (Harry N. Abrams, 2005). The standard modern biography.

Donald Crafton, *Before Mickey: The Animated Film 1898-1928* (Chicago, 1993).\"

  :notes
\"Gertie's status as first personality-animation is a widely-accepted historical claim in animation scholarship (Canemaker, Crafton, Solomon all agree). The vaudeville presentation and the McCay-walks-into-the-film illusion are documented. The 10,000 frames estimate is standard (based on runtime × frame rate); McCay's own drawings of Gertie exist in archives.\"

  :philosopher-weave-details
\"Jung: Gertie as archetype — the emergence of the anima character in early animation.
Aristotle: personality-through-action — Gertie is what she does.
Sartre: being-is-doing — Gertie's shyness IS her animated behavior. There's no shy Gertie underneath the frames.\"

  :tie-forward
\"Appendix 2 will take us into rotoscoping — Fleischer's technique and what it enables.\")
")
